"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:3.21.5\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">3.21.5</span> Shackle, fetter, manacle</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">כֶּבֶל</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(kevel)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps105:18\">PSA 105:18</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ps149:8\">PSA 149:8</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">נְחֹשֶׁת</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(nchosheth)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Judg16:21\">JDG 16:21</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Sam3:34\">2SA 3:34</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Kgs25:7\">2KI 25:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr33:11\">2CH 33:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/2Chr36:6\">2CH 36:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer39:7\">JER 39:7</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jer52:11\">JER 52:11</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lam3:7\">LAM 3:7</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">πέδη</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(pedē)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark5:4\">MRK 5:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark5:4\">MRK 5:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke8:29\">LUK 8:29</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir6:29\">SIR 6:29</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir21:19\">SIR 21:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/3Macc4:9\">3MA 4:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/3Macc6:19\">3MA 6:19</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir6:24\">SIR 6:24</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir33:29\">SIR 33:29</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/1Macc3:41\">1MA 3:41</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">χειροπέδη</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(cheiropedē)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir21:19\">SIR 21:19</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description and usage:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>\n            <figure class=\"thlex-image\"><img class=\"thlex-img\" src=\"images/WEB-0439_shackle.jpg\" alt=\"Shackle for the ankles to restrict prisoner movement\"><figcaption class=\"thlex-caption\">Shackle for the ankles to restrict prisoner movement (Daderot, Public domain or CC0, via Wikimedia Commons)</figcaption></figure>Fetters were metal chains with special links prepared to go around the ankles. They served to restrict the movement of someone considered dangerous or being imprisoned. There is considerable overlap between this entry and the preceding one on “chain.” See also the illustration there.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The equivalent in some languages for “fetters” is simply “chains on the feet.” <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Mark5:4\">MRK 5:4</a> and <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Luke8:29\">LUK 8:29</a> refer to both chains and fetters. Fetters were used to bind the legs and feet and chains were used to bind the hands and arms. Where a specific word for “fetters” is not known, it is possible to render the literal phrase “bound with fetters and chains” as “put chains on his hands and feet.”</p>\n<p>The Old Testament text usually specifies the material of which the fetters or chains were made. The Hebrew word <em>nchosheth</em> refers to brass or bronze, while the two references to <em>kevel</em> in the Psalms are to instruments of iron.</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
